Part 11 is based on Cicero’s Orations and follows in gen- eral the plan of Part Ι ; systematic work in grammar being carried on with illustrative exercises throughout the year. The orations used for a basis are the Manilian Law, the Catilinarian Orations, and the Archias, The ground covered is in some respects the same as that gone over in Part I, except that the treatment is more detailed and the accompanying exercises are somewhat harder. Among the new subjects discussed in Part 11 are the translation in Latin of the Eng- lish auxiliary verbs and the use and meaning of the Latin prepositions. Both of these classes of words are of constant occurrence, and thus far have lacked adequate treatment in books for secondary schooIS. To give greater definiteness to the work it seemed wise to discuss particular subjects with special orationS‚ as follows z with the Manilian Law, syntax of nounS, adjectiveS, and pronouns; with the Catilinarian OrationS, syntax of the subjunctive; with the Archias, the English auxiliary verbs and the Latin prepositionS. , There has been provided, further, a vocabulary of synonyms, without which a study of Cicero’s prose would be quite incomplete.

Part ΙΙΙ consists of thirty-four exercises to be used as a prose review in the fourth year. If systematic study of grammar has been steadily pursued for two years, such knowledge can be best tested and made effective by miscel· laneous exercises independent of an accompanying text. These exercises are of this character, and consist each of two partS, A and B. The sentences in A are short and dis· connected, while B consists of a paragraph of connected narrative. Teachers will use either or both parts at their discretiori. One of these exercises per week throughout the senior year would not seem an excessive requirement.
